<br>
I do the pick up group thang, because it's a great way to meet new people. I understand what the values are of a majority of Everquest players. I know what the goals are of a majority of Everquest players. I still do the pick up group thang, because I will and have met great people in this way. <br>
<br>
Upon joining an pick up group, I examine the behavior of each group mate. Are they negatively assertive, over-anxious to loot and pull. Bad leaders, do they have inferiority complexes, are they vulgar......and how much does loot govern their playstyle. <br>
<br>
I was told that there was a time when treasure of a majority of pick up groups was bestowed upon players in a need before greed fashion, (He who can use as an improvement is entitled). <br>
<br>
This has changed, seemingly to a factor of not trusting the players you group with. How you can play a game of any kind with someone you don't like....I do not know. <br>
<br>
If I am playing with friends, and we invite a stranger into a group....and an item drops. That player has the right to seek the item regardless of who can use it. However, the player is measured afterwards by having sought an item best suited for another...and will not be invited again.<br>
<br>
I sponsor playing for friendship, and aquiring new friends. I do not sponsor &quot;gimme, my twinkie need and I go EC after fight kk?&quot; attitudes. <br>
<br>
At the same time, I will not accept a group's offering of &quot;here, you should have this,  it's a monk item&quot; if I am not positive the group in full believes I should. If I read a sentence or sense that another player is not happy that the item goes to one player of a particular class. It is neccessary for all to roll and do as they will with the reward.  <br>
<br>
Guild rules, Shmuild rules !  Your playstyle is defined by your perspective on treasure.  All it takes is one night of &quot;fuk nb4g d00ds and bros, I wizzie and no wizzie stuff drps here. how i make pp?&quot; attitude and your reputation is shot, even if you happen to walk away with a new toy. <br>
<br>
I hope for you, the goal is not to see who has the most items and platinum collected when the game ends. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uledge.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ledge</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(11/7/01 12:40:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=566.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Loot, and how wanting it reflects your reputation. </span><hr size=1> NB4G works only if people are all 100% honest, and or within a guild group.<br>
<br>
Who's to say Buddydood_01 did not just drop his fungi tunic off on a mule in EC.<br>
<br>
Who's to say that selling item x that I can not wear and buying item y that I can't wear would not address my &quot;need&quot; and that my &quot;need&quot; is greater than Buddyguy_01 who can immediately wear said item.<br>
<br>
The only way to be completely fair in a p/u group is for everyone to have an equal chance at everything. Everyone puts in the same effort. Everyone should have the same chance at reward. Failing that, each member in that p/u group should go camp an item of equal &quot;need&quot; for each member in that group (oh wait thats what guilds are for).<br>
<br>
I can honestly say that being a 59 Shaman with fungi tunic and staff, I have no desire to do a P/U group in Sebilis King when I have zero chance at gaining anything (xp not withstanding). I don't think this makes me gready, or a bad person. I have had some great P/U groups, in which everyone agrees that everyone can roll on an item. I won't join one where I have no chance of being rewarded for my time.<br>
<br>
My pet peeve, is folks who join an p/u group. It is decided that everyone will have an oportunity to roll on everything. A RBG drops. We all roll. And the female level 60 warrior once losing the roll, bails mid-pull near lower exit 'cause she did not win. Things were fine, til she lost.<br>
<br>
